				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} f &= {f_{\text{d}}} + {f_{{\text{TCO}}}} \\ &=\frac{{{W_{\text{d}}}}}{{{W_{\text{d}}} + {W_{\text{a}}}}} +\frac{1}{3} \cdot{R_{\text{sh}}}\frac{{J_{\text{mpp}}}}{V_{\text{mpp}}}\cdot \frac{W_{\text{a}}^3}{{W_{\text{d}}} + {W_{\text{a}}}} \\ \end{aligned}$$\end{document}where Wd and Wa are the width of the dead area and active area, respectively; Rsh is the TCO sheet resistance; Vmpp and Jmpp present the voltage and current density at the maximum power point, respectively. For certain values of Wa, the power losses can be minimized by decreasing the dead area width [161]. For a definite dead area width, the total power losses will decrease first and then increase with the width of the active area. The subsequent increase in power losses results in increased TCO resistance-induced energy loss. These calculated results are consistent with experiments (Fig. 7f) [94]. The best PEC was achieved with a cell area width of 4.5 mm when the GFF was 91%.
